headline: CNN This Morning
subHeadline: "The Reign Begins: Charles And Camilla" Airs This Sunday 8 P.M. ET/PT; Key Inflation Gauge Tracked By Federal Reserve Cools; Fed To Release Findings In Its Silicon Valley Bank Collapse Probe; Roy Wood Jr. Gears Up To Host Tomorrow's W.H. Correspondents' Dinner; "Vet Crew" Cares For Pets Left Behind In Ukraine. Aired 8:30-9a ET

utterances.speaker: POPPY HARLOW, CNN ANCHOR
utterances.sentences: The coronation of a new British monarch has only been televised once before, right, when Queen Elizabeth was -- the second who was crowned. That was 70 years ago. Now, as final preparations are underway for the crowning of King Charles III, many are asking questions about what this moment, this man mean in the modern world.This week on the whole story, our Erica Hill traveled to London in a -- in search of some of those answers, meeting with leading British scholars, journalists, and some of those closest to Queen Elizabeth thinking Charles himself. Watch this. (BEGIN VIDEO CLIP)

utterances.speaker: UNIDENTIFIED FEMALE
utterances.sentences: There is a great deal of similarity, I think, between the Prince of Wales at times raging against the machine and saying, well, I want to do this and I want to talk about that. And by the way, I know what I'm talking about and I'm not afraid to say it. Who does that remind you of? Reminds me massively of Harry.

utterances.speaker: ERICA HILL, CNN ANCHOR AND NATIONAL CORRESPONDENT
utterances.sentences: In his book "Spare", Harry writes that, "Charles had always been discouraged from hard work, he told me. He'd been advised that the heir shouldn't do too much, shouldn't try too hard for fear of outshining the monarch. But he'd rebelled."Is Charles a rebel? Does anyone feel he is?

utterances.speaker: UNIDENTIFIED FEMALE
utterances.sentences: I wouldn't call him a rebel. I think that he has developed a sense of self-awareness and gone at things in a different way. But I wouldn't say that that would be -- I wouldn't call that rebelling.

utterances.speaker: UNIDENTIFIED FEMALE
utterances.sentences: I think he'd like to see himself.

utterances.speaker: HILL
utterances.sentences: Yes.

utterances.speaker: UNIDENTIFIED MALE
utterances.sentences: -- as a rebel and revolutionary. UNIDENTIFIED MALE

utterances.speaker: UNIDENTIFIED MALE
utterances.sentences: Charles had points when he was absolutely raging against the machine in exactly the same way Harry did. There are so many parallels.(END VIDEO CLIP)

utterances.speaker: AUDIE CORNISH, CNN ANCHOR
utterances.sentences: Joining us now, again, CNN Anchor and National Correspondent Erica Hill.

utterances.speaker: HILL
utterances.sentences: Good morning.

utterances.speaker: CORNISH
utterances.sentences: Good morning. Now he's taking the throne. A completely different kind of commonwealth, right?

utterances.speaker: HILL
utterances.sentences: Yes.

utterances.speaker: CORNISH
utterances.sentences: Racially, religiously. The demographics have changed, so is there any one view of this moment?

utterances.speaker: HILL
utterances.sentences: I think, you know, it's such a great question, is there one view? The short answer is no, because it is a much more diverse country, both in the U.K. and within the Commonwealth. And as we -- you know, as, I think, we would probably see on this side of the Atlantic, but certainly as we learn from these fascinating discussions that we had with scholars and journalists and those who used to work for the royal household, there's a different sensibility.And there are more questions in general being raised about not only what is the role of the monarchy in 2023. A lot of those questions spurred by the death of Queen Elizabeth, a 70-year-reign gone, gives people time to pause and think about what does this really mean? But also, and especially among the younger generation, there are more questions about how did we get here? And how did this small country amass so much wealth and so much power for hundreds of years? And are we taking a close look at that history and what it means and how are we addressing it?

utterances.speaker: CORNISH
utterances.sentences: But will any of that come out in a coronation? I mean, that's by definition, pomp and circumstance.

utterances.speaker: CORNISH
utterances.sentences: Although people are obsessed with whether Harry will be there.

utterances.speaker: HILL
utterances.sentences: He will be there. Don't worry.

utterances.speaker: CORNISH
utterances.sentences: Thanks for that reporting.

utterances.speaker: HILL
utterances.sentences: He will be there. Where he will be sitting? We do not yet know. But I think he'll be there.

utterances.speaker: KAITLAN COLLINS, CNN ANCHOR
utterances.sentences: But Meghan will be there.

utterances.speaker: HILL
utterances.sentences: She's sitting back in California, she said with their kids. Their son, Archie, of course, his birthday is also Saturday. He turns four. Same day as the coronation. So lots to celebrate for the whole family.

utterances.speaker: HARLOW
utterances.sentences: Lots to celebrate.

utterances.speaker: HILL
utterances.sentences: They're just doing it in different places.

utterances.speaker: HARLOW
utterances.sentences: There you go, Erica.

utterances.speaker: COLLINS
utterances.sentences: Yes.

utterances.speaker: HARLOW
utterances.sentences: Cannot wait to see it.

utterances.speaker: HILL
utterances.sentences: Please watch.

utterances.speaker: HARLOW
utterances.sentences: We will.

utterances.speaker: HILL
utterances.sentences: We're pretty proud of it.

utterances.speaker: HARLOW
utterances.sentences: We will.

utterances.speaker: HILL
utterances.sentences: Yes. A lot of interesting questions and discussion.

utterances.speaker: CORNISH
utterances.sentences: Yes. Be sure to tune in to "The Reign Begins

utterances.speaker: COLLINS
utterances.sentences: And as we wait for that, the Fed's preferred measure of inflation was just released. It could play a major role in whether or not your interest rate is going to go up. We'll show you the numbers right after this.(COMMERCIAL BREAK) [08:40:23]

utterances.speaker: HARLOW
utterances.sentences: All right. This just in the Fed's preferred measure of inflation just released by the Commerce Department. This could be critical, right? And what the Fed does next on interest rates.Chief Business Correspondent Christine Romans here to break it down.

utterances.speaker: CHRISTINE ROMANS, CNN CHIEF BUSINESS CORRESPONDENT
utterances.sentences: I think it shows that the fed's rate hike campaign, aggressive rate hike campaign is working, this PCE price index. This is consumer inflation the fed really likes to look at. It grew only 0.1 percent from February to March.That's good. That's a more normal rate of inflation than some of the terrible numbers we had been seeing. When you look year over year, it's still too hot up, 4.2 percent. But that's down pretty dramatically. It was 4.6 percent last month. It was 5 percent the month. And so, you know, it's good to see that number coming down here. There's another number that came out. The employment cost index. ECI is a quarterly number. I know you've covered this before too, that shows that wages picked up, though, in the quarter. So here's this split screen. Wages are still rising. That's good. I mean, I -- everybody wants to get a little more money in your paycheck. That's good for people. But the fed has been worried that that is inflationary. So on the one hand, those prices are cooling and that's showing the fed's medicine is working, but wages are still strong. Good for people. But will the fed like that? I'm not so sure.

utterances.speaker: COLLINS
utterances.sentences: Yes, we'll see what they say. Also, they're about to release the findings of that investigation.

utterances.speaker: ROMANS
utterances.sentences: Yes.

utterances.speaker: COLLINS
utterances.sentences: And to basically what caused. What happened with Silicon Valley Bank? What are we expecting?

utterances.speaker: ROMANS
utterances.sentences: So we get that at 11. We're also going to hear from the FDIC later today. What happened to Silicon Valley Bank? Did the feds miss something or was this just a case of bad mismanagement? A bank that grew too quickly? It grew way bigger in assets and deposits than it did say in compliance and risk management, which is bad. You know, it's just banking 101 that they made some big failures there.So we're going to get -- this is really sort of the postmortem of what happened there. And hopefully, it'll tell us more about whether the feds or the federal government is more aware now of the similar problems that might be happening at other banks. We'll be watching First Republic sharers today.

utterances.speaker: CORNISH
utterances.sentences: And whether it is other banks, right? ROMANS

utterances.speaker: CORNISH
utterances.sentences: Or whether it was just this bank.

utterances.speaker: ROMANS
utterances.sentences: Exactly.

utterances.speaker: COLLINS
utterances.sentences: Yes.

utterances.speaker: ROMANS
utterances.sentences: First Republic sharers are up this morning, but you know, they've lost half their value this week. So there's a lot of pressure and a lot of behind the scenes maneuvering to figure out what happens next for First Republic. So watch that space.

utterances.speaker: HARLOW
utterances.sentences: OK, we will. Christine, thank you. Have a good week.

utterances.speaker: ROMANS
utterances.sentences: You too.

utterances.speaker: HARLOW
utterances.sentences: Thanks.

utterances.speaker: COLLINS
utterances.sentences: Thanks.

utterances.speaker: CORNISH
utterances.sentences: And we are one day away from the White House Correspondents' Dinner. President Biden will be there, and so will comedian Roy Wood Jr. ready to roast Washington's elite.(BEGIN VIDEO CLIP)

utterances.speaker: DONALD TRUMP, FORMER PRESIDENT OF THE UNITED STATES
utterances.sentences: I have a Trump hating judge with a Trump hating wife and family.ROY WOOD JR., HOSTING WHITE HOUSE CORRESPONDENTS' DINNER TOMORROW: Who you know go to trial and talk -- about the judge? He can destroy you and you riling him up. You about to fight cocaine, man. You don't offer him crack first. (END VIDEO CLIP)

utterances.speaker: CORNISH
utterances.sentences: Roy Wood Jr., is here in the studio live to preview his big night here with us.

utterances.speaker: COLLINS
utterances.sentences: I got both of those on (INAUDIBLE).

utterances.speaker: BARACK OBAMA, FORMER PRESIDENT OF THE UNITED STATES
utterances.sentences: In our fast- changing world, traditions like the White House Correspondents' Dinner are important.KEEGAN-MICHAEL KEY, COMEDIAN: I mean, really? What is this in? And why am I required to come do it? CEDRIC THE ENTERTAINER, COMEDIAN: Connie's (ph) the one, you know, being very diplomatic in the meetings, you know? Well, that's good. That's great. We're all on the same pattern because at the end of the day, you know, freedom is what we all want. The leaves will come out late. North Korea said what? OK. All right, all right. Hold my purse, Mr. President. Hold my purse.

utterances.speaker: TREVOR NOAH, COMEDIAN
utterances.sentences: Fox News is sort of like a waffle house. Yes. It's relatively normal in the afternoon, but as soon as the sun goes down, there's a drunk lady named Janine (ph), threatening to fight every Mexican who comes in. You can throw me out. I know the real president.(END VIDEO CLIP)

utterances.speaker: COLLINS
utterances.sentences: It's the White House Correspondents' Dinner. A uniquely Washington tradition. The first dinner actually took place back in 1921. Only had 50 people. This year it's going to be star-studded. It's going to have a guest list over 2,500 people.It's a rare chance for the Press Corps to let its hair down and socialize with Washington brokers and celebrities, sometimes gets criticized for that. 16 presidents and vice presidents since Calvin Coolidge have attended the dinner. One who did not. Donald Trump never made an appearance during his presidency, instead sent his press secretary. In recent years, a speaker, typically a comedian, does roast the commander in chief. And this year's roaster is joining us now, standup comedian and correspondent of The Daily Show. Roy Wood Jr. who we're all hoping --

utterances.speaker: WOOD
utterances.sentences: Yes.

utterances.speaker: COLLINS
utterances.sentences: -- forgets our names by tomorrow night.

utterances.speaker: CORNISH
utterances.sentences: Yes, you never met us.

utterances.speaker: WOOD
utterances.sentences: Yes.

utterances.speaker: CORNISH
utterances.sentences: Wipe it clean. Wipe it clean.

utterances.speaker: WOOD
utterances.sentences: Kaitlan and Poppy, good to see this.

utterances.speaker: HARLOW
utterances.sentences: And Audie --(CROSSTALK)

utterances.speaker: COLLINS
utterances.sentences: -- Cooper, it's great to meet you.

utterances.speaker: CORNISH
utterances.sentences: OK. This is our weirdest gig, right? Like the people in the room aren't your audience, and how do you practice?

utterances.speaker: COLLINS
utterances.sentences: Right, right.

utterances.speaker: WOOD
utterances.sentences: This is just a --

utterances.speaker: CORNISH
utterances.sentences: Which is the line you have to walk, right? It's half a political event.

utterances.speaker: WOOD
utterances.sentences: Yes.

utterances.speaker: CORNISH
utterances.sentences: I mean, fundamentally, do you have a sense of like, how do you even make a joke in the age when there is no shame?

utterances.speaker: WOOD
utterances.sentences: Well, I think you still make the joke. There's still a punchline. Now the shame part is about whether or not the joke can influence change. I don't think the correspondents' dinner -- I mean, we would have to check and do the research, but I don't know if any politician, they got hit with a joke and was like, you know what? Let me go ahead and reconsider my whole platform.

utterances.speaker: COLLINS
utterances.sentences: Donald Trump?

utterances.speaker: WOOD
utterances.sentences: Well --

utterances.speaker: COLLINS
utterances.sentences: Run and go.

utterances.speaker: WOOD
utterances.sentences: He said, let me start a platform.

utterances.speaker: CORNISH
utterances.sentences: Right.

utterances.speaker: WOOD
utterances.sentences: But like to just -- there's nothing I can -- you think the Ron DeSantis jokes I got in the clip --

utterances.speaker: COLLINS
utterances.sentences: OK.

utterances.speaker: WOOD
utterances.sentences: -- but tomorrow and you think that Ron DeSantis tomorrow's about, you know what, man, you're right. Go on and put the black history back in the books.

utterances.speaker: CORNISH
utterances.sentences: A glimmer of where this is, is going here, I'm hearing.

utterances.speaker: WOOD
utterances.sentences: We would hope. We -- I saw you had that hope in your eye. You like, you hope it runs.

utterances.speaker: CORNISH
utterances.sentences: It was brief and then like a flame went out.

utterances.speaker: WOOD
utterances.sentences: That's he's fighting Mickey Mouse.

utterances.speaker: CORNISH
utterances.sentences: OK. You know this is --

utterances.speaker: WOOD
utterances.sentences: He's fighting Mickey Mouse. You can't change that person's mind with a joke. It's possible -- I'm raising my voice.

utterances.speaker: CORNISH
utterances.sentences: No, I love it. It's morning energy.

utterances.speaker: COLLINS
utterances.sentences: We love it. We love energy.

utterances.speaker: HARLOW
utterances.sentences: All jokes, but I love your story too. I want our viewers to get to know you a little bit before they see you up there. The fact that, you know, you're born here in New York, but then you grew up now in Birmingham.

utterances.speaker: WOOD
utterances.sentences: Yes, I was born in New York. I grew up in Birmingham. My father was a radio journalist, but he deliberately embedded himself in pretty much any black conflicts ever going on. Black platoons in Vietnam.

utterances.speaker: HARLOW
utterances.sentences: In Vietnam, yes.

utterances.speaker: WOOD
utterances.sentences: Soweto. He was in Rhodesia and Zimbabwe now. And then I got to college. Stuart Scott was my North Star for journalism. I wanted to be funny and talk about sports. Got down to college. Got in trouble.Apparently, you have to pay for clothes when you go to the mall. You do not just get to leave with them, you have to give them money.

utterances.speaker: HARLOW
utterances.sentences: But that --

utterances.speaker: WOOD
utterances.sentences: I did not, but that's what got me in a stand-up.

utterances.speaker: HARLOW
utterances.sentences: Because that year you had that FAM University let you -- won't let you -- gave you a year off to think about things.

utterances.speaker: WOOD
utterances.sentences: Suspensions. Suspension is the word.

utterances.speaker: HARLOW
utterances.sentences: That's when you started.

utterances.speaker: WOOD
utterances.sentences: Yes, yes.

utterances.speaker: HARLOW
utterances.sentences: That's when you started this comedy, right?

utterances.speaker: WOOD
utterances.sentences: But to the credit of Florida A&M University, they allowed me to come back and get that journalism degree --

utterances.speaker: HARLOW
utterances.sentences: Yes. WOOD

utterances.speaker: COLLINS
utterances.sentences: It's poetic. Who are your targets for tomorrow night?

utterances.speaker: WOOD
utterances.sentences: See you all. I know what you're trying to ask me and I'm trying to answer this for now. Yes, I'm going to talk about what happened this week. I got to talk about everything this week. Let me just say that --

utterances.speaker: CORNISH
utterances.sentences: Did something happened this week?

utterances.speaker: WOOD
utterances.sentences: There was a lot of stuff that happened this week. There were many things that happened this week, and those things have to be discussed in a fair way. In a very fair way.

utterances.speaker: COLLINS
utterances.sentences: Kevin McCarthy, I think is bracing for that.

utterances.speaker: HARLOW
utterances.sentences: Yes.

utterances.speaker: COLLINS
utterances.sentences: So don't worry.

utterances.speaker: HARLOW
utterances.sentences: Yes.

utterances.speaker: WOOD
utterances.sentences: No, trust me, I'm not going to lose my job. I'm not trying to get in trouble, OK?

utterances.speaker: COLLINS
utterances.sentences: Rood Wood Jr. --

utterances.speaker: WOOD
utterances.sentences: That's the most important part of the Correspondents' Dinner, is leave employed.

utterances.speaker: COLLINS
utterances.sentences: That's your goal, leave employed. I love that.

utterances.speaker: WOOD
utterances.sentences: That's the goal.

utterances.speaker: COLLINS
utterances.sentences: Roy Wood, Jr. , we're all going to be there. We cannot wait to see what you have prepared and I know you've been preparing really hard for this. So --

utterances.speaker: WOOD
utterances.sentences: Thank you all.

utterances.speaker: COLLINS
utterances.sentences: -- can't wait.

utterances.speaker: WOOD
utterances.sentences: Thank you.

utterances.speaker: COLLINS
utterances.sentences: And to see what those jokes are going to be, who his targets are. And President Biden also going to be there. Make sure you tune in. That's tomorrow night, 8

utterances.speaker: HARLOW
utterances.sentences: You are a joy.

utterances.speaker: WOOD
utterances.sentences: Thank you all.

utterances.speaker: HARLOW
utterances.sentences: My friend. We can't wait.All right. 50 -- that means you can't make fun of me tomorrow night. 55 million people --

utterances.speaker: COLLINS
utterances.sentences: Yes, she's buttering up.

utterances.speaker: HARLOW
utterances.sentences: Russia's invasion of Ukraine triggered a flood of refugees. Many of them were pet owners, who had to leave their dogs, their cats, their beloved pets behind for what they hoped would only be days for two veterinarians who specialized in exotic animal rescue. The situation led them to a new mission -- caring for these beloved but abandoned pets.This week, CNN Heroes salutes Ukraine's Vet Crew, Leonid and Valentina Stoyanov. Anderson Cooper shares their story. (BEGIN VIDEOTAPE)

utterances.speaker: VALENTINA STOYANOV, VET CREW
utterances.sentences: A lot of people think that all this situation in Ukraine will be three, four days. So a lot of people just closed animals in apartments, in houses, and think that everything will be fine.ANDERSON COOPER, CNN HOST (voice-over): For more than a year now, the Stoyanovs have been rescuing and caring for dogs and cats by the hundreds in Ukraine. Despite the danger, they put their lives at risk, even driving to the front lines, to vaccinate and feed animals.

utterances.speaker: LEONID STOYANOV, VET CREW
utterances.sentences: Russian army a lot of times shooting our car. And we have a lot of holes.V. STOYANOV: Each animals for us, it's like our family. COOPER (voice-over): The Vet Crew's work earned them support from millions on social media. They say it's all those encouraging messages that keep them going. V. STOYANOV: A lot of people write us, guys, hold on. You are heroes. It's huge, huge support and we are very grateful. (END VIDEOTAPE)

utterances.speaker: HARLOW
utterances.sentences: Well, to get the full story on Ukraine's Vet Crew and to nominate your own CNN Hero, go to cnnheroes.com.

utterances.speaker: COLLINS
utterances.sentences: And a special thanks to Audie for joining us this morning at the table. CORNISH

utterances.speaker: COLLINS
utterances.sentences: Yes, a lot of fun having you here.

utterances.speaker: HARLOW
utterances.sentences: We always make it happy.

utterances.speaker: COLLINS
utterances.sentences: Yes.

utterances.speaker: HARLOW
utterances.sentences: Thank you, Audie.
